**Abstract:**
A substantial essay titled "On MacIntyre, Rationality, and Dramatic Space" examining the prevailing notion of rationality and its implied conception of the subject-world relationship. Critiques the Platonic-Cartesian-Husserlian tradition of the "mirroring mind" (referencing Rorty) and develops the concept of "dramatic space" through analysis of spectator, witness, and participant modalities. Distinguishes description from narration to argue that the space in which we live is intrinsically dramatic. Notes indicate this was published in ACPA Proceedings.

**AI Recommendation:** Major published essay developing the dramatic space concept; compare with 96-DEC-4 variant.

